SIMPLE: salvo
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Salvo
<hw>Sal"vo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Salvos</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>salvo jure</ets>,
literally, the right being reserved. See <er>Safe.</er>]</ety> <def>An
exception; a reservation; an excuse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They admit many <qex>salvos</qex>, cautions, and reservations.</q>
<rj><qau>Eikon Basilike.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Salvo</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Salvo
<hw>Sal"vo</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>salve</ets> a discharge of
heavy cannon, a volley, L. <ets>salve</ets> hail, imperat. of
<ets>salvere</ets> to be well, akin to <ets>salvus</ets> well. See
<er>Safe</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A concentrated
fire from pieces of artillery, as in endeavoring to make a break in a
fortification; a volley.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A salute paid by a simultaneous, or nearly
simultaneous, firing of a number of cannon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Salvor</ent>⟦br⟧
